the phrase "Sean Spicer says,"
it makes the

35:58.223 --> 36:01.092 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
statement more incredible, not
more credible.

36:01.192 --> 36:05.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that we have a
Congress that's
quite politicized on this set of
issues.

36:05.830 --> 36:11.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're going to need some type of
independent
voice to determine what's
happening in this

36:11.569 --> 36:12.737 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
case.

36:12.837 --> 36:15.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, on that
note, we shake
our heads.

36:15.640 --> 36:16.941 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

36:17.042 --> 36:17.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Michael Gerson,
Mark Shields,
thank you both.

36:17.809 --> 36:24.315 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Thank you, Judy.

36:24.416 --> 36:31.423 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL GERSON: Thank you.

36:31.523 --> 36:37.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There's a lot
going on in
the political world of
Washington these days,

36:37.829 --> 36:43.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but the hottest ticket in town
may be for
a museum exhibition by a
Japanese artist exploring

36:43.701 --> 36:46.204 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
worlds well beyond today's
headlines.

36:46.304 --> 36:48.239 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has our story.

36:48.339 --> 36:54.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's called an
Infinity Mirror
Room, and the stretching out of
time and space,

36:54.913 --> 36:59.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an effect created through the
use of lights,
reflection and objects, is one
of the obsessions

37:00.085 --> 37:03.054 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of artist Yayoi Kusama.

37:03.154 --> 37:07.792 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Right now at Washington's
Hirshhorn Museum,
people are lining up to
experience her world

37:07.892 --> 37:12.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of whimsy, color, shapes, and
peeks into the
beyond.

37:12.630 --> 37:14.499 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Museum director Melissa Chiu:

37:14.599 --> 37:16.301 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MELISSA CHIU, Director,
Smithsonian's Hirshhorn
Museum: There are fewer and
fewer moments

37:16.401 --> 37:23.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
today that you're alone in
something that
feels universal.

37:23.408 --> 37:27.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You are there in amongst the
cosmos in one
piece.

37:27.245 --> 37:28.513 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's just light.

37:28.613 --> 37:31.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's a kind of -- it's very
poignant and
very compelling.

37:31.449 --> 37:36.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Even as the wider
world has
caught on, Kusama has in fact
been a much-loved

37:36.855 --> 37:43.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
star in the art world since the
early 1960s,
after coming to New York from
her native Japan.

37:43.495 --> 37:49.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her earliest works already
displayed motifs
that remain to this day, notably
the repetition

37:49.534 --> 37:56.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of forms, especially simple
marks and polka
dots, that Kusama gives a more
cosmic significance,

37:56.374 --> 38:00.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as in her series of paintings
called "Infinity
Nets."

38:00.612 --> 38:05.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In an interview with Hirshhorn
curators in
December, the 87-year-old
artist, as colorful

38:05.984 --> 38:10.989 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
as her work, spoke of her
attempt to reach
the infinite through the
repetition of images.

38:11.089 --> 38:15.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
YAYOI KUSAMA, Artist (through
translator):
The same things piled one on top
of another

38:16.060 --> 38:20.899 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
creates an expanding world that
reaches out
to the edges of the universe.

38:20.999 --> 38:27.272 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That is the simple image I have.

38:27.372 --> 38:32.944 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
This effect of continual
repetition calls
out to the human senses, and, in
return, deep

38:33.044 --> 38:35.780 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
inside of our hearts, we yearn
for true amazement.

38:35.880 --> 38:39.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Curator Mika
Yoshitake put
together the exhibition.

38:39.317 --> 38:42.520 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MIKA YOSHITAKE, Curator,
Hirshhorn Museum:
Her work is very
process-oriented, meaning

38:42.620 --> 38:50.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that there is a very lengthy,
you know, physical
labor that goes on, that the
repetition of

38:50.128 --> 38:56.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
certain motifs like the nets or
the polka
dots, and they -- it kind of
expands organically.

38:56.167 --> 39:01.172 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: That
compulsiveness is there
in sculptures of phallic forms:
a rowboat

39:01.272 --> 39:07.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
titled "Violet Obsession,"
furniture that
you might not want to sit in,
but Kusama herself

39:07.378 --> 39:11.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was happy to, and happy to be
photographed
in.

39:11.149 --> 39:16.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, she often brought
herself into the
picture, a polka dotted,
kimono-wearing, downtown

39:16.621 --> 39:22.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
'60s art world figure known for
creating happenings
on the streets, sometimes with
nudes, sometimes

39:23.061 --> 39:25.163 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
protesting the Vietnam War.

39:25.263 --> 39:30.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She also began to make the
Infinity Mirror
Rooms, eventually 20 in all, six
at the center

39:30.835 --> 39:34.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of this new exhibition, the most
ever gathered
together.

39:34.606 --> 39:38.176 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Part of the attraction of
Kusama's work clearly
is the fun house effect.

39:38.276 --> 39:45.316 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I mean, here I am, with
cameraman Malcolm,
in a field of pumpkins that
stretches on,

39:45.416 --> 39:46.718 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
yes, to infinity.

39:46.818 --> 39:48.720 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MIKA YOSHITAKE: It's about life.

39:48.820 --> 39:51.389 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's about confronting our
mortality.

39:51.489 --> 39:56.327 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's about filling a void that
she has experienced.

39:56.427 --> 40:02.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that incessant energy, a
desire to connect
with people, I think it's about
the clarity

40:03.001 --> 40:04.836 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of vision and also perception.

40:04.936 --> 40:08.172 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But Kusama's
story is more
complicated.

40:08.273 --> 40:13.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She suffered from hallucinations
from childhood,
and experienced early trauma
from being forced

40:13.544 --> 40:17.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by her mother to spy on her
father as he had
affairs.

40:17.415 --> 40:21.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She had a breakdown in the 1970s
that forced
her to return to Japan.

40:21.352 --> 40:27.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, for more than 40 years,
she's voluntarily
lived in a psychiatric hospital,
even as she's

40:27.458 --> 40:32.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
continued to work in a studio a
block away,
making what she's referred to as
art medicine.

40:33.064 --> 40:35.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKA YOSHITAKE: Art for her is a
form of therapy.

40:35.833 --> 40:42.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So she needs the art, or else
she will probably
not survive.

40:42.106 --> 40:49.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She is somebody who needs to
have a ritual
every day of, you know,
painting.

40:49.781 --> 40:54.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Certainly, her
work brought
a good deal of pleasure at the
Hirshhorn exhibition,

40:54.919 --> 41:00.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
especially in the Obliteration
Room, a pristine
white-walled space in which
visitors were

41:00.491 --> 41:04.762 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
invited to join in the
art-making by adding
dots of their own.

41:04.862 --> 41:10.835 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Captured in time-lapse video,
the room was
being transformed, just as
Kusama intended,

41:10.935 --> 41:12.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
according to museum director
Chiu.

41:12.770 --> 41:17.108 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MELISSA CHIU: The word
obliteration has a
very harsh kind of meaning, but,
for her this

41:17.208 --> 41:22.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was, in a way, how she thinks
about her art,
that her art is transforming her
own life,

41:22.547 --> 41:27.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
helping her to deal with life,
but also potentially
allowing others to interact with
it here in

41:28.019 --> 41:29.354 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this room.

41:29.454 --> 41:31.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Museum-goers
couldn't resist,
and neither could I.

41:31.622 --> 41:35.827 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, if I put it like this...

41:35.927 --> 41:37.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MELISSA CHIU: Put wherever you
like, Jeff.

41:37.495 --> 41:38.396 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

41:38.496 --> 41:39.397 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MELISSA CHIU: So, balancing.

41:39.497 --> 41:40.398 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
See how he's balancing?

41:40.498 --> 41:41.399 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

41:41.499 --> 41:42.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

41:42.500 --> 41:43.401 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

41:43.501 --> 41:44.736 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

41:44.836 --> 41:46.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MELISSA CHIU: You could create
patterns from
randomness.

41:46.704 --> 41:47.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you can see, some people
couldn't resist
and they have tried to create a
line with

41:47.171 --> 41:47.705 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their dots.

41:47.805 --> 41:48.639 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But all bets are off.

41:48.740 --> 41:50.475 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You can do whatever you like.

41:50.575 --> 41:54.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: There's a lot of
humor and
a lot of pain in the work of
Yayoi Kusama,

41:54.579 --> 41:59.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who continues to put in full
days at her studio
creating new paintings and
sculptures, even

41:59.650 --> 42:03.254 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as record crowds here flock to
see the results.

42:03.354 --> 42:08.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From the Hirshhorn Museum in
Washington, D.C.,
I'm Jeffrey Brown for the "PBS
