42:35.086 --> 42:52.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Finally, an
essay from Emily
Esfahani Smith.

42:52.170 --> 43:01.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She is trained in psychology,
and author of
the recent book "The Power of
Meaning."

43:01.479 --> 43:10.354 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
An editor at Stanford
University's Hoover
Institution, tonight, Emily
offers her Humble

43:10.455 --> 43:16.394 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Opinion on what we should search
for.

43:16.494 --> 43:26.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMILY ESFAHANI SMITH, Author,
"The Power of
Meaning: Crafting a Life That
Matters": In

43:26.871 --> 43:43.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
recent years, psychologists have
started looking
more closely at how the
single-minded pursuit

43:43.754 --> 43:53.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of happiness affects us, and
they have come
to what seems like a
counterintuitive conclusion:

43:53.197 --> 43:58.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chasing happiness and obsessing
over it, the
way our culture encourages us to
do, can actually

43:58.870 --> 44:00.671 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
make people unhappy and lonely.

44:00.771 --> 44:05.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's different when we set
another goal
for ourselves, when we search
for and pursue

44:05.610 --> 44:06.644 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
meaning in life.

44:06.744 --> 44:09.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Human beings are creatures that
yearn for
meaning.

44:10.081 --> 44:17.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When we look up at the stars,
for example,
we don't see random balls of
fire.

44:17.255 --> 44:25.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We see swans and bears, we tell
stories and
myths, and we wonder about where
we came from,

44:25.863 --> 44:34.772 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
our place in the universe, and
how we can
make our lives count.

44:34.872 --> 44:39.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The same questions lie at the
center of much
great art, literature, and
philosophy.

44:39.176 --> 44:43.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The first great work of human
literature,
"The Epic of Gilgamesh," is
about a hero's

44:43.915 --> 44:51.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
quest to figure out how to live,
given the
fact that he will die.

44:51.222 --> 44:58.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in the centuries since
Gilgamesh's tale
was told, that quest has
remained as urgent

44:59.096 --> 45:00.798 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
as ever.

45:00.898 --> 45:05.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We all want to know that our
lives amount
to more than the sum of our
experiences.

45:05.937 --> 45:13.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We all need a why to help us get
through the
good and the bad of life.

45:13.411 --> 45:16.314 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, what is a meaningful life?

45:16.414 --> 45:23.054 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Social science points to one
defining feature.

45:23.154 --> 46:07.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You connect and contribute to
something beyond
yourself.

46:07.131 --> 48:24.802 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That could be

48:24.902 --> 50:14.845 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
your family, your work, nature,
or God.

50:14.945 --> 51:20.477 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
And when

51:20.577 --> 51:25.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people say their lives are
meaningful, it's
because three conditions have
been satisfied:

51:25.482 --> 51:30.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They believe their lives matter,
they have
a sense of purpose that drives
them forward,

51:30.688 --> 51:34.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and they think their lives are
coherent and
make sense.

51:34.858 --> 51:40.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It sounds like a lot, but that
last point
is something you can do right
now.

51:40.130 --> 51:45.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People tell me the simple act of
storytelling
gives meaning, or can at least
clear the path

51:45.402 --> 51:47.171 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to it.

51:47.271 --> 51:50.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That, I think, might explain the
rise of rap
and hip-hop and the popularity
of the radio

51:50.741 --> 51:54.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
series "StoryCorps" and "The
Moth."

51:54.144 --> 51:58.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Making a narrative out of the
events in your
life provides clarity.

51:58.115 --> 52:01.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It offers a framework that goes
beyond the
day-to-day.

52:01.919 --> 52:06.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's the act itself, and not
necessarily sharing
their story with others, that
helps people

52:07.057 --> 52:10.194 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
make sense of themselves and
their lives.

52:10.294 --> 52:19.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we all have the power to
tell or to re-tell
our life story in more positive
ways.

52:19.103 --> 52:30.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: On the "NewsHour"
